The MAPPINGS on the 3 coordoninates of vertices of a mesh
may be defined aby:

1: identity R3 -> R3 named I;
-----------------------------
Do not change X or Y or Z

2: Mapping R3 -> R3 defined by 3 functions  
------------------------------------------
If (x,y,z) are the vertex coordinates then
(ABSCISSE(x,y,z), ORDINATE(x,y,z), COTE(x,y,z))
is the final vertex where ABSCISSE, ORDINATE and COTE
are 3 user's functions with the 3 parameters (x,y,z).
x, y, z may be used or not to write the function text.

Example:
MAPPING_2; 2;         {definition of 3 functions}
deffunc ABSCISSE( x , y , z ) ; 
   si    (1<=x) et (x<100)
   alors  ABSCISSE = log(x) ;
   sinon  ABSCISSE = abs( x*y-z ) ;
   finsi;  
endfunc;  
deffunc YY( x, y, z); YY=y+3; endfunc;
deffunc ZZ( x, y, z); ZZ=z;   endfunc;  
ABSCISSE; YY; ZZ; {les noms des functions dans la transformation}

3: isometry of R3 -> R3  
-----------------------
there are 7 types of isometries (in a large sens) : 

0: translation defined by a R3 vector
Input the 3 real componentes of translation vector
Example: TR_3_0; 3; 0; 1; 2; 3;
Translation de vecteur(1,2,3)

1: translation+rotation+dilatation defined by 2 points and 7 reals 
Example: TR_3_1; 3; 1;
P1_AXIS_ROTATION; P2_AXIS_ROTATION; {axe de rotation defini par 2 POINTS}
 90.0;      {rotation degrees around this axis};
 1; 2; 3;   {3 componentes of translation vector}
 2; 1; 0.5; {3 coefficients of dilatation in directions x y z}

2: translation+rotation+dilatation defined y 4 images of 4 points 
The 4 first points define a reference system before mapping
the first  point P1 is the origin of the reference system
the second point P2 define the axis E1 = P1 P2  such that NORM(E1)=1
the third  point P3 define the line P1 P3 and the plane E1 E2  
 E3 = P1P2 x P1P3  such that NORM(E3)=1
 E2 = E3   x E1    such that NORM(E2)=1

The 4 last points define a reference system after mapping
the first  point Q1 is the origin of the reference system
the second point Q2 define the axis F1 = Q1 Q2  such that NORM(F1)=1
the third  point Q3 define the line Q1 Q3 and the plane F1 F2  
 F3 = Q1Q2 x Q1Q3  such that NORM(F3)=1
 F2 = F3   x F1    such that NORM(F2)=1

The DILATATIONS are the RATII of DISTANCES
 || Qi - Q1 || / || Pi - P1 ||   for i=2,3,4
Thus, it is possible to compute the matrix and the vector of
the mapping.
The 4-th and 8-th POINTS are ONLY USED to define the DILATATION
in the 3th direction.
ATTENTION: If the 8 points don not form orthogonal reference systems
           then  Q1 =  T( P1 )
           but   Qi <> T( Pi )  i=2,3,4
Example:
MAPPING_3_2; 3; 2;  R1_ORIGIN; R1_X; R1_Y; R1_Z; {ref system before}
                    R2_ORIGIN; R2_X; R2_Y; R2_Z; {ref system after }

3: translation+rotation defined by 3 images of 3 points
IDEM previously but WITHOUT DILATATIONS
Example:
MAPPING_3_3; 3; 3;  R1_ORIGIN; R1_X; R1_Y; {ref system before}
                    R2_ORIGIN; R2_X; R2_Y; {ref system after }
 
4: plane symetry defined by 3 points 
The input of 3 POINTS not on a same line is sufficient.
Example:
MAPPING_3_4; 3; 4; P1_PLANE; P2_PLANE; P3_PLANE;

5: line symetry defined by 2 points 
The input of 2 different POINTS is sufficient.
Example:
MAPPING_3_5; 3; 5; P1_LINE_SYMETRY;  P2_LINE_SYMETRY;

6: point symetry
The input of 1 POINT is sufficient.
Example:
MAPPING_3_6; 3; 6; POINT_SYMETRY;

4: projection on an implicit surface of R3 
------------------------------------------  
The x,y,z coordinates the PROJECTED VERTEX must verify 
F( x , y , z ) = 0 , implicit definition of the SURFACE.
The FUNCTION NAME may be choose as you want (24 characters max)
Example:
deffunc sphere(x,y,z); sphere=x*x+y**2+z*z-25; endfunc;
Define a sphere centred at origin and of radius 5.

The PROJECTION POINT is the INTERSECTION of a LINE and the SURFACE
The computation of x,y,z such that F( x , y , z ) = 0 is done
by dichotomy of 2 POINTS P1 and P2 on the line such that
F(P1) * F(P2)<=0
A SENS of PROJECTION is given and if no convergence, it is inversed.

9 types of projections : 
 1: parallel projection to +oX X  ascending  
-1: parallel projection to -oX X decreasing    
 2: parallel projection to +oY Y  ascending  
-2: parallel projection to -oY Y decreasing
 3: parallel projection to +oZ Z  ascending  
-3: parallel projection to -oZ Z decreasing  
 4: projection from the centre anf the point to be projected
 5: orthogonal projection to the plane defined by 3 points
 6: orthogonal projection to the line  defined by 2 points
ATTENTION: The point or vertice to be projected must NOT be on the line!

Examples:
PROJ1;  4;  1;  {projection +oX}
PROJM1; 4; -1;  {projection -oX}    
PROJ2;  4;  2;  {projection +oY}
PROJM2; 4; -2;  {projection -oY}    
PROJ3;  4;  3;  {projection +oY}
PROJM3; 4; -3;  {projection -oY}    
PROJ4;  4;  4;  POINT_CENTRE_PROJECTION;
PROJ5;  4;  5;  P1_PLANE_PROJECTION; P2_PLANE_PROJECTION;
 P3_PLANE_PROJECTION;      
PROJ6;  4;  6;  P1_LINE_ORTHOGONAL; P2_LINE_ORTHOGONAL;

